I am so grateful to SCBWI to be the featured illustrator for December. You can watch the interview via a link in my Linktree or go to the SCBWI YouTube page. @temikatheartist is not only a gifted illustrator, she is a gifted interviewer too! And she managed to seamlessly edit out our giggle-fest. How did she do that? I recently celebrated my 5 year SCBWI anniversary and I can honestly say that without finding this group I would probably still be searching for my place in the big wide world of illustrators. I started not knowing anything, a tiny illustrator seedling. But with the help of this group, I’ve been able to learn and grow and find a spot for myself in the kid-lit world. Thank you so much @scbwi !
.
.

2022 was an awfully good year for me. My book The Wild Garden came out and I started work on a new book. I was able to travel again and meet people and share my art, and I made lots of new pieces and experimented a ton. I was the featured illustrator for SCBWI in December. I launched my newsletter the Chronicle. So many good things that I am so grateful for. We did loose our beloved 18 year old kitty Hobbes and there was much turmoil in the world. There was sadness for sure, but there was also so much joy. I’m hoping the best for my friends and family in 2023. Peace and glad tiding. Happiest of New Year’s to you and yours. I’ll see you in 2023. Love, Cynthia 
.

This is the first piece in my new ongoing project for 2023. It's not really a New Year's resolution, but just another way to keep sketchbook work interesting and challenging. And it will be a warm up before client work.
.
These are the project rules: Once a week while out of my daily morning walk I will bring home a found object that will inspire a sketchbook illustration. I can work on this for as long or as little as I like and it doesn't matter which day of the week I make it. I'll use one word that will be like a compass word to direct the image. I will use traditional materials as the base. In this piece I'm using a Star Magnolia (I think) branch that I found on my walk yesterday 1.4.2023 and I'm using the compass word "expectation" because when I look at this branch I can see spring buried within it. You can check out my reel to see a very badly done up video of the painting I made last night. This piece took me maybe 4 hours to make.
.
I feel much better today. I’ve been in a creative slump, but that could just be the holidays and the fact that I’ve had a head cold for about 2 weeks. We all hit them from time to time. I think this one is over for me.

The Chronicle Issue Two is out today! It’s all about critiques as told through some of my own experiences including a critique of this yeti drawing which was actually in my portfolio when I first started. I count critiques as another valuable tool in style and voice development and I hope this issue will help you as you prepare yourself and your work for a critique. The issue includes a handy checklist that I developed too. I do love checklists. I wrote this article for my local SCBWI chapter so you may have seen this already. My mother taught me that baking was a way to show your love and today I’ll be making a pear clafoutis to show mine. A little bit of sweetness for the ones that are so sweet to me. This is a gouache and colored pencil piece I made for a Julia Child recipe that is a bit complex for this type of thing, but it’s really good. I’ve been trying to avoid sugar as much as I can since the beginning of the year. I fail sometimes, and today it looks like it might be one of those days. I hope you have a lovely day. And if there is no one special in your life, treat yourself today and show yourself some love. You are special and you deserve it.

An illustration from my very first author/illustrator book (and very first book in my whole life!) Pie for Breakfast” 2021 @presteljuniorinternational. Making this book was like a pie in the sky dream come true. 🤩 I got to create mini worlds for each recipe which included a character with their own little backstory, environment, family and connection to my main character. Each recipe also had its own color palette. My job included developing, curating and testing the recipes and creating a story to connect them all. It was an amazing few months. Lots of baking and drawing, all during Covid. I remember trying to get some of the ingredients and it was often difficult. Remember those days? Thank you @presteljunior for believing in me and starting me on my professional illustrator path. And continuing to work with me. I’ll always be grateful. ❤️
.

Last night’s gouache painting. It’s one of those found object paintings that I’m trying to make every week, remember that New Year’s resolution I made? I’m still trying… This is actually based on a beautiful piece of colonial wallpaper I found when doing research for another project. The wallpaper featured the chartreuse vase and leaves only. It was so beautiful and I wanted to capture it right away. I added the flowers, the bear, ball and everything else. Somehow it turned into and ABC kind of illustration. 😁 No idea how or why that happened.

Applications are open today! There are 25 picture book creators—writers and illustrators alike, ready to work with you including me! I’m thrilled to be part of this group. I could be your best buddy mentor and partner this summer. I’d love to help you reach your goals, share some giggles, a cup of tea, and some “roll up our sleeves time” with you. My focus will be on illustration—I can help you tell stories with both your words and your pictures, or I can help you hone your artistic voice, or I can help you develop your own learning/business plan, or maybe all of those things. We’ll figure it out. It’s time for you! And it’s all free. Out of the 25 mentors there are a few focused on illustration if that is what you are looking for. They include these talented folks: @anneappertillustration @jerroldconnors @ariadelsole @natashakhankazi @shamarknightjustice There is someone for you, please consider applying.
.
.

I’m joining #foltakeweek again this year. It is a storytelling challenge that resonates so strongly with my upbringing. As a child I lived for the tall tales, lore, and spooky stories that my many relatives casually shared. My ears were always open for them. That story about the body in the ancient crypt whose hair and beard continued to grow long and white, stories about murder and moonshine in the cave at our swimming hole, the 3x great aunt that walked into a river never to return, the lore about the wagon and horses that got swallowed up in a sink hole in a field near our house. There were so many stories. We sat with eyes wide as saucers not wanting to miss a word. I’ve no idea what the prompts will be, but maybe I can connect them to some of these stories? And maybe I’ll stick with black and white this year. Just maybe. I made this kooky and first-time animation on a long car ride. It was fun and I learned a lot. @folktaleweek
.
.

Part 1: LOST
For @folktaleweek this year I wrote a folktale inspired story. It’s a little long. So each day I'll summarize the part of the story that goes with the prompt. Story below…
.
Henry O'Hennessy was very fond of marching around the house shouting “I am a BIG BOY! I am a BIG BOY!” He wanted everyone to know that he was big enough to do big things. But when he tried to help, things tended to go wrong, or get broken, or get messy.
.
Against her better judgement, his mother decided to send Henry to the market all by himself. She pinned a small purse filled with coins inside Henry’s jacket and she gave him a list for the shopkeeper.
.
Then she told him this rhyme.

“Left by the stone-gray wall.

Right by the horses’ stall.

Ten paces, a jump, a skip, and a hop.

Over the hill by the Millner’s shop.

Across the bridge, you are almost there.

Follow the road to the village square.” 
.
She made Henry repeat it to her 5 times.

Then off he went.

“RIGHT by the stone-gray wall.

Left by the waterfall.”

Henry skipped along. “I am a BIG BOY!”

He climbed onto a fallen log.

“Ten paces, a jump, a skip, and a…”

Drop!

Henry fell off the log. He dusted himself off and looked around. “I am a big boy.” he said.

He tottered along.

“Over the hill by the whatsit shop? By the curdle plop? By the doodle stop?”

Henry did not see any shops. “I am a big boy.” he whispered.

He looked over the ridge and he could see all the way to the edge of the world, but he had no idea where he was.

“Across the ridge, you are almost there,

Follow the road to the clean sea air!”

And off Henry ran down to the beach shouting "I am a B I G  B O Y!”

.

Art vs Artist 2023

You can totally go home again. I did. Don’t you ever let anyone tell you that you can’t.

As a little one I saw myself as an artist, even though I was only in the single digits. But as I grew bigger my belief in myself as an artist grew smaller. And for decades I didn’t make art of any kind. But then one day I started to feel something tugging at me, a buzzing around my head, pestering and persisting. It frightened me. So I ignored it.

As I entered the third act of my life I searched for new meaning, new purpose and joy. I tried many things, always avoiding art making. Drawing had been a bright spot in my sometimes dark childhood. I could escape the unease in my household by making art. And people liked what I made. It gave my small, painfully shy and awkward self a little time to shine. I had many happy memories of art-making as a child and I cherished them. I didn’t want to spoil those memories by failing at art as an adult. I didn’t believe in myself again.

But the tugging and pestering continued and then one day I just gave in. And there it was again. Home.
.

I love drawing wildflowers. What can I say. I just do. When my mind needs some rest, that’s what I do. And it brings calm and quiet back to my bouncy, spinning thoughts. It’s my Tai Chi version of art making. I had a boss once that was a Tai Chi master. When he got stressed, he’d stop working, go in a corner and practice moves until the stress dissolved. That’s what I’m doing when I draw flowers. It works. Another “The Great Outdoors” illo for the #uppercaseandtheydraw prompt.

If you’ve been following me for awhile, you’ll know that I really like to draw bears. I’ve had a few bear encounters in my life, but we’ll leave those stories for another day.
.
The bear in this illustration is 128 Grazer, an Alaskan brown bear who won a prize. She was crowned the Fattest Bear in 2023. Before you start thinking this is some body image shaming post, this contest is about survival for bears, because for them weight gain will ensure a healthy hibernation. The Katmai National Park and Preserve in Alaska holds this contest every year. They track the bears at the beginning of the season when they are lean and very hungry, and follow them as they bulk up in preparation for hibernation. The bears almost double their weight! If you go on their website they have before and after photos and a bracket because you can vote on the bears. They have classroom/teaching exercises and have even started a Fat Bear Junior contest. Publishers, I see a children’s book in here somewhere! If you are as fascinated by bears as much as I am, check them out. https://www.nps.gov/katm/learn/fat-bear-week-2023.htm
.
I made this drawing based on a lovely photo I found of 128 Grazer. I wish I could credit the photographer, but I’m not sure who they are, maybe someone at the park service? I’ll add the photo I used as reference in my story. And I’ll enter this drawing in the “The Great Outdoors” #uppercaseandtheydraw illustration challenge.
